But most people don't even know the basic

00:11:53.720 --> 00:11:59.840
rule. So if you get this part right, you'll
be right like 85% of the time and that's probably

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:04.440
better than you're doing now. Some of you.
[audience chuckles] I'm sure some of you have

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:11.840
it down. But 'affect' is usually a verb and
'effect' is usually a noun. So Aardvark is

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:17.000
a character in my book. Aardvark and Squiggly
are buddies and they fish together and stuff.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:24.250
So I, I,the first memory trick I came up with
uses this sentence because it's all A's. So

00:12:24.250 --> 00:12:30.810
Aardvark is our friend and it's all A's. ëThe
arrows affected Aardvark.í And 'affected'

00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:37.150
is a verb in that sentence. The arrows are
taking an action on Aardvark. They're affecting

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:44.270
him. And you can see that it's a verb by substituting
other verbs and they work in the sentence,

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:48.790
that's a little trick I often use. If I don't
know what kind of word to use, I'll substitute

00:12:48.790 --> 00:12:54.420
similar words and see if it makes sense. So
the arrows affected aardvark. The arrows hit

00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:59.730
Aardvark. They poked Aardvark. And they annoyed
Aardvark. Those are all verbs. So if you can

00:12:59.730 --> 00:13:05.960
remember that sentence, you can compare it
to a sentence you're trying to write and see

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:11.860
if it's kinda like that sentence. And that's
one way to, to choose the right word and remember

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:16.570
that 'affected', the verb, starts with an
'A' because the arrows affected Aardvark.

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:24.480
Now a second memory trick that some people
seem to like better is 'affect' is for verbs

00:13:24.480 --> 00:13:30.290
and verbs are actions. And both 'affect' and
'action' start with the letter A. And you

00:13:30.290 --> 00:13:35.200
can see these kids, they're, they're affecting
the balls. They're taking action on the balls.

00:13:35.200 --> 00:13:42.300
They're making craziness happen to the balls.
So then 'effect' is the noun. And this is

00:13:42.300 --> 00:13:49.300
the example sentence with all E's for the
noun. The effect was eye-popping. The effect,

00:13:49.300 --> 00:13:54.780
the thing that happened to Aardvark, the noun,
was eye-popping. And you can see that is a

00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:59.550
noun by substituting other nouns in the sentence.
So the blood was eye-popping. The holes were

00:13:59.550 --> 00:14:04.760
eye-popping. And the sound, the sound Aardvark
made, was eye-popping. So those are example

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:12.380
sentences where one uses 'affect' the verb
and the other one uses 'effect' the noun.

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:20.210
So another trick is that nouns can usually
take an article. So 'the effect was eye-popping'.

00:14:20.210 --> 00:14:26.310
'She loved the effect the light had on the
paintings.' And 'the lightning effects were

00:14:26.310 --> 00:14:32.140
amazing.' So you can see, in the final one,
there's a word that comes between the article

00:14:32.140 --> 00:14:36.190
and the noun. It's modifying 'effects'. It's
telling you what kind of effects they were.

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:42.120
But you can still put an article in front
of 'effect'. When, when what you want is the

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:47.370
noun, you can usually put an article in front
of it. It doesnít work at all with the verb.

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:53.101
So you can't say, 'The arrows the affected
Aardvark' [audience murmurs] 'He was the affected

00:14:53.101 --> 00:14:58.420
by the layoffs.' That doesn't make any sense.
It's not even remotely grammatical. So if

00:14:58.420 --> 00:15:04.080
you can put an article like 'the' in front
of the word, then the one you want is 'effect'

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:10.740
with an E. And the way I remember it is that
'the' ends with E. And 'effect' starts with

00:15:10.740 --> 00:15:15.510
E. So if you have those two E's that can butt
up against each other, then you want the word

00:15:15.510 --> 00:15:21.000
that starts with the E. [pause]
And this is the memory trick that actually

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:27.780
works for me. It doesn't work for a lot of
people but I'll share it with you anyway.

00:15:27.780 --> 00:15:31.350
[laughs] To some people, some people do say,
'Oh that's my favorite one.' So, I remember

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:37.940
'affect ñ verb; effect ñ noun'. It's a mnemonic
ñ A-V-E-N. And you can make words with A-V-E-N.

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:43.410
So I always think of a raven because you can
spell raven 'R-A-V-E-N'. So if you can think

00:15:43.410 --> 00:15:47.870
of that raven in your head and you try to
remember which is the verb and which is the

00:15:47.870 --> 00:15:53.530
noun, then you have 'affect - verb; effect-noun'.
So just think of that black raven on the yellow

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:59.300
background and you'll have it forever.
So that was one of my early memory, early

00:15:59.300 --> 00:16:04.380
tricks, one of my early tips, one of the first
things I covered. And then I realized, people

00:16:04.380 --> 00:16:11.360
starting asking me about 'affective' versus
'effective'. Like it gets harder. So effective

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:16.480
is almost always the word you want. 'She's
a particularly effective leader.' 'We had

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:23.930
an effective meeting. And ëEffective immediately,
we'll have coffee at every meeting.' So really

00:16:23.930 --> 00:16:30.100
almost the only time you want to use 'affective'
with an A is when you're talking about a disease.

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:37.250
So, or something in psychology. So I grew
up in Seattle. So seasonal affective disorder,

00:16:37.250 --> 00:16:44.290
little children with their, their chins on
window sills looking out at the rain. So seasonal

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:50.950
affective disorder is an example of when you
would use 'affective' with an A. But most

00:16:50.950 --> 00:16:56.290
of the time, it's 'effective' with an E that
you want.

00:16:56.290 --> 00:17:01.190
So, so that's the end of the 'affect' versus
'effect' section. Hope I've given you some

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:07.449
memory tricks to remember. And then it sort
of leads into the next thing because 'impact',

00:17:07.449 --> 00:17:15.660
when people don't know whether to use 'affect',
they often use 'impact' and that bothers probably

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:21.880
20% of the population. Twenty, 80% of the
people have no idea about this but 20% of

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:27.180
the people, when you talk about 'impact' as
a verb, 'The weather impacted fourth quarter

00:17:27.180 --> 00:17:33.130
sales', people like lose their minds. They
hate it. So it, 'impact' as a noun is okay.

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:38.700
You can say 'The weather had an impact on
fourth quarter sales'. But as a verb, it's

00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:42.810
better to avoid it. And now you know how to
use 'affect'. You can say 'The weather affected

00:17:42.810 --> 00:17:48.370
fourth quarter sales.' You don't have to worry
about this. But when you say 'impact', the

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:51.870
sticklers, they think of 'impact' only means
to hit. So this in their mind is an impact;

